st, but that might not be necessary. I'm focused on preparing the Forge workflow for a library issue, particularly whether it requires setup beyond the usual generated test scaffold. My guidance suggests using action advisory_preparation if there’s non-empty input. However, there's a risk that system property names vary between JVM argument styles. Plus, Java 25 seems to have a different flag format to note.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing native image setup**\\n\\nI'm exploring the usage of `-D` as a system property in native images managed by SubstrateVM, particularly focusing on the native runtime. There's a need for a phrase that clarifies adding runtime arguments for the native test executable. I’m considering when to apply generated tests if `libraryVersion == '5.0.1'`, but I feel we shouldn't apply universally to Netty 4.2.x. Also, my summary will include mentioning the resolved artifact with Vert.x dependencies, but not docker. Should I highlight that local Vert.x HttpServer could be used for test setup instead of an external endpoint?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test setup options**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using a local Vert.x HttpServer on 127.0.0.1 instead of relying on external services, which makes sense for test-code setup. I feel like I should opt for \\\"no_action\\\" unless there’s something concrete to address. Research suggests that for normal usage, a WebClient needs an HTTP server to provide meaningful test coverage, potentially using an in-process local HttpServer. But then, I wonder if that setup goes \\\"beyond normal scaffold\\\"?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing OAuth2 dependency**\\n\\nI’m looking at the library POM, which has an optional vertx-auth-oauth2 that seems necessary for the OAuth2WebClient class. It’s possible that “meaningful coverage” means including a broader API, so an optional dependency might be important, but the existing tests don't seem to have that. I 